WEBVTT

00:09.792 --> 00:11.707
[CROWD CHEERING]

00:11.837 --> 00:13.448
<i>ALFIE:
The Raven Union is going</i>

00:13.578 --> 00:14.971
to attack London
before the year's out.

00:15.102 --> 00:17.017
There will be
a proper argy-bargy.

00:19.019 --> 00:20.324
Fuck off, mate.[GUNSHOT]

00:20.455 --> 00:22.065
[GROANING IN AGONY]

00:22.196 --> 00:24.372
<i>THOMAS: The Union have
the regular Army on their side.</i>

00:24.502 --> 00:26.678
They have tanks,
artillery

00:26.809 --> 00:28.593
<i>and man power,
and they're up against...[BLOW STRIKES]</i>

00:28.724 --> 00:30.769
<i>...poorly armed,
poorly led civilians.</i>

00:30.900 --> 00:33.468
<i>BET:
We're charging you with...</i>

00:33.598 --> 00:35.296
subversion

00:35.426 --> 00:37.776
and conspiring
to commit violent acts.

00:38.995 --> 00:40.605
Take your clothes off.

00:40.736 --> 00:41.737
Tell you what, sir...

00:43.521 --> 00:45.001
This is the chap.

00:45.132 --> 00:47.395
Colonel John Salt
of the Union Militia.

00:47.525 --> 00:49.701
<i>SALT: Before the war,
I worked at a place</i>

00:49.832 --> 00:51.399
<i>we called Room 101.</i>

00:51.529 --> 00:53.183
A torture chamber really.

00:54.358 --> 00:55.577
When you're ready, mate.

00:55.707 --> 00:56.969
We're in a bit of a hurry.

00:57.100 --> 00:58.928
Best find
the bus stop then, eh?

00:59.059 --> 01:01.278
It's good
to see you, Thomas.

01:01.409 --> 01:03.367
The big news is,
I'm engaged.

01:03.498 --> 01:05.761
Oh, no kidding.

01:05.891 --> 01:07.458
Goodbye, young man.

01:07.589 --> 01:09.286
Perhaps we'll meet again.

01:09.417 --> 01:12.202
You know me,
I love a crisis.

01:16.859 --> 01:19.470
[♪♪♪]

01:31.700 --> 01:34.529
CLIFF RICHARDS [OVER P.A.]: <i>
London, rejoice!</i>

01:34.659 --> 01:39.055
<i>Final victory
of the Raven Union is near.</i>

01:39.186 --> 01:43.407
<i>With the might of
the armed forces on our side,</i>

01:43.538 --> 01:46.323
<i>we will triumph
over the English League</i>

01:46.454 --> 01:48.978
<i>and their young Queen.</i>

01:49.109 --> 01:52.460
<i>The leftist factions
still tyrannize...</i>

01:52.590 --> 01:54.331
[BULLET RINGS OFF SPEAKER]

01:54.462 --> 01:55.941
AZIZ: Hello, Martha.

01:56.072 --> 01:58.509
Glad to see you amusing
yourself.

01:58.640 --> 02:00.424
We have time
on our hands.

02:00.555 --> 02:03.993
The Union just lob
the occasional mortar.

02:04.124 --> 02:05.821
Waiting for us to surrender,
I guess.

02:05.951 --> 02:07.301
How I wish
we could do that.

02:07.431 --> 02:08.911
[GUNSHOT]Surrender.

02:09.041 --> 02:11.696
The very word
sounds delicious.

02:11.827 --> 02:13.742
News of Salt's escape
reached you I expect.

02:13.872 --> 02:15.570
It did.

02:15.700 --> 02:16.962
I'm sorry to waste
all your good work.

02:17.093 --> 02:17.963
Entirely my fault.

02:18.094 --> 02:19.748
What went wrong?

02:19.878 --> 02:21.576
Sad to say,
I'm about 87% sure

02:21.706 --> 02:22.968
we were set up
by Alfred Pennyworth.

02:23.099 --> 02:24.535
Wow.[GUNSHOT]

02:24.666 --> 02:25.928
The lousy son of a bitch.

02:26.058 --> 02:27.756
A useful man you know
to be untrustworthy

02:27.886 --> 02:29.366
is better
than no man at all.

02:29.497 --> 02:30.976
I don't know
about that.

02:31.107 --> 02:32.587
Talking of useful men,

02:32.717 --> 02:34.502
I hear you ran into
an old friend of ours.

02:34.632 --> 02:38.332
Oh. Oh, yes, yes.
Yeah, Thomas Wayne came by.

02:38.462 --> 02:39.898
How is the rascal?

02:40.029 --> 02:41.857
[DRY CHUCKLE]

02:41.987 --> 02:43.989
That's why you came
all the way out here to see me.

02:44.120 --> 02:46.601
Heh. I do try to avoid
front lines if I can.

02:46.731 --> 02:48.385
Since when are you spying
on me, Victor?

02:48.516 --> 02:49.778
Please.Seriously.

02:49.908 --> 02:51.562
Seriously, Martha,
get a grip.

02:51.693 --> 02:53.173
We were following
Thomas Wayne.

02:54.435 --> 02:55.958
Right. Sorry.

02:56.088 --> 02:57.351
Paranoia.

02:57.481 --> 02:59.396
I know the feeling.

02:59.527 --> 03:02.094
Thomas Wayne
was fine and dandy.

03:02.225 --> 03:04.619
Blooming.
What d'you want to know?

03:04.749 --> 03:05.881
[SNIFFS] Uh...

03:07.883 --> 03:09.580
Still with
the same company, is he?

03:09.711 --> 03:11.408
Yup.

03:11.539 --> 03:13.845
And the company says
fuck liberty and democracy,

03:13.976 --> 03:15.630
they're staying neutral.

03:15.760 --> 03:17.501
Of course they are.
And that doesn't mean

03:17.632 --> 03:19.111
we shouldn't cultivate
their friendship.

03:19.242 --> 03:22.027
I hope you were friendly.Friendly? No.

03:22.158 --> 03:23.768
[SIGHS, GRUNTS]

03:23.899 --> 03:26.771
No?
I told him
to take a hike.

03:26.902 --> 03:28.077
Why on earth
did you do that?

03:28.208 --> 03:30.079
He only came by
to snoop around.

03:30.210 --> 03:31.907
Fuck him
and fuck the CIA.

03:32.037 --> 03:33.778
My dear Martha,
you must tell him

03:33.909 --> 03:35.650
he need not hike anywhere
on your account.

03:35.780 --> 03:37.042
The hell I will.

03:37.173 --> 03:39.175
[EXPLOSIONS IN DISTANCE]

03:39.306 --> 03:42.004
I gather he's engaged
to be married.

03:42.134 --> 03:43.788
What of it?

03:43.919 --> 03:47.139
Perhaps,
and I tread lightly here,

03:47.270 --> 03:50.142
perhaps his engagement
has peeved you, somehow?

03:50.273 --> 03:51.709
I'm not
the slightest bit peeved.

03:53.102 --> 03:56.758
Uh-- Okay,
yeah, I'm peeved.

03:56.888 --> 03:58.629
[STAMMERS]

03:58.760 --> 04:01.110
I'm peeved because
he and his paymasters

04:01.241 --> 04:03.634
are standing by
and letting fascists
take over this country.

04:03.765 --> 04:05.201
And we, Martha,
must do our best

04:05.332 --> 04:07.551
to encourage them
not to do that.

04:07.682 --> 04:09.771
For liberty and democracy
and all that.

04:11.555 --> 04:13.383
It's your duty.

04:17.561 --> 04:18.997
[CROW SQUAWKS]

04:19.128 --> 04:20.738
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

04:25.874 --> 04:27.658
What are you looking at?

04:32.054 --> 04:33.969
Where are
you taking me?

04:34.099 --> 04:35.927
Wherever
this bus goes.

04:36.058 --> 04:37.755
If it ever comes.

04:37.886 --> 04:39.975
Then we'll see.

04:40.105 --> 04:42.543
Just so long as we're out
of the immediate vicinity.

04:43.935 --> 04:46.111
I want to go home.

04:46.242 --> 04:48.244
You can't.Why not?

04:48.375 --> 04:50.638
First place
they'll be looking for you.

04:50.768 --> 04:52.901
Looking for me?

04:53.031 --> 04:55.295
Slow as paint.

04:55.425 --> 04:58.559
You're lucky you've got me
watching out for you.

04:58.689 --> 05:00.517
If I let you
go off on your own,

05:00.648 --> 05:02.650
you'll be caught,
and they'll blame you

05:02.780 --> 05:05.130
for killing Major Sutcliffe
and they'll hang you.

05:05.261 --> 05:09.091
Now, you're with me
until I get this sorted.

05:09.221 --> 05:12.529
Sorted? How?

05:12.660 --> 05:15.445
Lord Harwood's
a close personal friend of mine.

05:16.881 --> 05:18.840
Soon as I tell him
what's occurred,

05:18.970 --> 05:21.103
he'll have it all expunged.

05:21.233 --> 05:23.714
That's the technical word
for it.

05:23.845 --> 05:24.933
Expunged.

05:25.063 --> 05:27.501
Lord Harwood?

05:27.631 --> 05:28.589
A friend of yours?

05:30.242 --> 05:32.419
You're looking at me
like I'm a liar.

05:32.549 --> 05:33.681
No.

05:33.811 --> 05:35.160
If you say it's so.

05:35.291 --> 05:38.686
He made me a captain,
got me this job.

05:38.816 --> 05:41.471
If there's owt he can do for me,
his Lordship'll do it.

05:44.692 --> 05:47.390
Fuck's sake, gloomy guts.

05:47.521 --> 05:51.002
Time was you were banged up
naked with a cock in your face.

05:51.133 --> 05:52.134
Look at you now.

05:52.264 --> 05:53.570
I'm cold.

05:53.701 --> 05:55.485
Why didn't
you say something?

05:56.791 --> 05:58.140
Hey, you.

05:58.270 --> 05:59.489
Hello.

06:00.838 --> 06:03.058
You alright?
Mmm.

06:03.188 --> 06:04.494
Give us your coat.

06:04.625 --> 06:06.191
Pardon?

06:06.322 --> 06:07.671
Your coat, man.

06:08.890 --> 06:10.021
My coat?

06:10.152 --> 06:12.502
I don't-- What?

06:17.159 --> 06:18.987
Give us.
Your coat.

06:24.166 --> 06:25.820
[BET SIGHS]

06:33.654 --> 06:34.829
Thank you.

06:36.831 --> 06:40.225
BET: Well, Where's
this fucking bus, eh?

06:40.356 --> 06:43.446
<i>♪ One, two
One, two, three, four! ♪</i>

06:43.577 --> 06:45.927
['50s STYLE ROCK MUSIC
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS WITHIN]

06:50.888 --> 06:53.021
[LIVELY CHATTERING]

06:53.151 --> 06:54.849
Love, thank you.

06:56.764 --> 06:57.852
WAITRESS:
Oi!

06:57.982 --> 06:59.070
Get another one.

07:06.121 --> 07:08.123
[POPS][EXHALES]
America.

07:08.253 --> 07:10.560
BOTH [CHUCKLE]:
America.

07:11.692 --> 07:12.823
When?

07:12.954 --> 07:14.259
Lot of pay-offs
to make,

07:14.390 --> 07:16.087
but we should be underway
end of next week.

07:16.218 --> 07:18.089
When do we tell Chadley
and the staff?

07:19.177 --> 07:20.701
We don't.

07:20.831 --> 07:22.267
We'll leave 'em a note
and some cash.

07:22.398 --> 07:24.095
Walk away
without saying goodbye?

07:24.226 --> 07:25.749
That's cold.

07:25.880 --> 07:27.621
It's just good sense.

07:27.751 --> 07:29.231
If we tell the staff,
it's as good

07:29.361 --> 07:30.319
as telling the whole city
we're leaving.

07:30.450 --> 07:31.842
[SCOFFS]
We are leaving.

07:31.973 --> 07:33.627
People will say
we're running away.

07:33.757 --> 07:35.193
We are running away.

07:35.324 --> 07:37.326
We're not running away,
we're moving on.

07:37.457 --> 07:39.763
Since when d'you care
what other people say?

07:39.894 --> 07:41.373
I don't.

07:41.504 --> 07:43.898
I just don't want
any aggravation, that's all.

07:44.028 --> 07:45.813
Surprise is always
the best strategy.

07:45.943 --> 07:49.033
True. Especially when
you're running away.

07:49.164 --> 07:51.645
But you'll tell Sandra
you're leavin', eh?

07:53.255 --> 07:54.778
When the time's right.

07:56.824 --> 07:59.653
I feel bad for her.
Poor wee thing.

07:59.783 --> 08:01.002
Fuck's sake, Daveboy.

08:01.132 --> 08:04.919
BAZZA [SIGHS]:
He feels bad too.

08:05.049 --> 08:07.661
I feel great
thank you very much.

08:07.791 --> 08:09.837
We're making
a fresh start.

08:09.967 --> 08:12.013
New horizons.

08:12.143 --> 08:14.668
Stands to reason there'll
be hard choices along the way.

08:14.798 --> 08:16.757
[RAIN PATTERING]

08:16.887 --> 08:18.323
DAVEBOY:
Here's to hard choices then, eh?

08:18.454 --> 08:19.673
BAZZA:

08:19.803 --> 08:20.935
Hard choices.

08:24.242 --> 08:27.115
[♪♪♪]

09:13.944 --> 09:16.860
[DEAD PHONE TONE RINGS OUT]

09:16.991 --> 09:18.732
Sod it.

09:18.862 --> 09:19.950
Lines are down.

09:20.081 --> 09:21.648
[SHIVERING]
What'll we do?

09:21.778 --> 09:22.736
I'm thinking.

09:23.824 --> 09:24.868
I'm tired.

09:24.999 --> 09:26.914
I can't walk
anymore.

09:27.044 --> 09:28.393
We'll have
to hide somewhere

09:28.524 --> 09:31.353
until I can talk
to his Lordship.

09:31.483 --> 09:33.442
Word of what we've done
will be all over by now.

09:33.573 --> 09:36.750
I haven't
done anything.

09:36.880 --> 09:38.578
Stop moaning.

09:40.841 --> 09:41.972
Come on.

09:49.414 --> 09:50.764
BET:
There we are then.

09:50.894 --> 09:51.808
[HANDCUFFS CLICK]

09:51.939 --> 09:53.593
Nice and cozy, eh?

09:55.116 --> 09:56.726
Mm-hmm.

09:56.857 --> 09:58.032
It'll do.

09:59.903 --> 10:03.298
I'll try his Lordship
again later

10:03.428 --> 10:05.039
and the phones'll work...

10:06.954 --> 10:08.869
...and we'll be right as rain.

10:09.913 --> 10:11.611
[♪♪♪]

10:18.443 --> 10:20.097
GAUNT:
Have you ever been
to Liverpool, Jimmy?

10:20.228 --> 10:21.925
Can't say
that I have.

10:22.056 --> 10:23.492
Ghastly place.

10:23.623 --> 10:25.886
But I like
the people though.

10:26.016 --> 10:27.409
Amusing.

10:27.539 --> 10:28.889
Stubborn.

10:30.325 --> 10:33.023
I wish to God
they would surrender.

10:33.154 --> 10:35.852
All of them.
Manchester, London.

10:35.983 --> 10:38.376
Horrors
they would save us from.

10:38.507 --> 10:40.683
Well, you know
they won't, old girl.

10:40.814 --> 10:42.859
Not yet.

10:42.990 --> 10:46.471
One last fierce assault
should break them.

10:46.602 --> 10:48.256
They leave us no choice.Now, there are always choices.

10:48.386 --> 10:49.213
[SALT COUGHS]

10:49.344 --> 10:50.780
Oh.
Ah

10:50.911 --> 10:52.129
HARWOOD:
Salt, it's good

10:52.260 --> 10:53.348
to have you
back on the job.

10:53.478 --> 10:55.045
What would we do without you?

10:55.176 --> 10:56.264
What d'you got
for us today?

10:56.394 --> 10:57.308
Good morning,
your Lordship.

10:57.439 --> 10:59.136
Mrs. Gaunt.

10:59.267 --> 11:01.051
I have the results
of the latest Stormcloud tests.

11:01.182 --> 11:02.487
[FOLDER THUMPS ON DESK]

11:02.618 --> 11:05.099
Well, I'll--
I'll look at those later.

11:05.229 --> 11:06.840
Stormcloud tests?

11:06.970 --> 11:08.232
That sounds intriguing.

11:08.363 --> 11:09.190
HARWOOD:
Well, it's all very speculative.

11:09.320 --> 11:10.887
You know these boffins.

11:11.018 --> 11:12.672
On what
are they speculating?

11:12.802 --> 11:16.240
I'm sorry, sir.
I assumed Mrs. Gaunt knew.

11:16.371 --> 11:17.981
Never mind, Salt.

11:19.548 --> 11:21.681
It's all
top secret stuff.

11:23.508 --> 11:25.554
Top secret, from me?

11:25.685 --> 11:27.077
These things have
to be kept close.

11:27.208 --> 11:28.209
Strictly
need to know basis.

11:28.339 --> 11:29.689
I need to know.

11:31.168 --> 11:32.430
It's chemicals.

11:34.911 --> 11:36.260
Chemicals?
Yes.

11:36.391 --> 11:38.436
Gases and so forth.

11:38.567 --> 11:40.351
Salt can fill you in
on all the details.

11:40.482 --> 11:42.179
But I say it's all
very speculative.

11:42.310 --> 11:44.268
You mean poisonous gases?

11:44.399 --> 11:46.053
For God's sake,
woman, we're at war.

11:46.183 --> 11:48.403
You want choices?
Well, here's a damn choice.

11:55.366 --> 11:58.500
Well, Colonel Salt,
tell me about

11:58.630 --> 12:01.329
these 'speculative'
gases of yours.

12:01.459 --> 12:03.113
Yes, ma'am.

12:03.244 --> 12:04.593
The science department
reports

12:04.724 --> 12:07.770
the latest tests of
the prototype are promising,

12:07.901 --> 12:10.730
as regards reaction time
and post mortem presentation.

12:12.601 --> 12:15.038
I have the numbers here
if you'd like to look at them.

12:15.169 --> 12:20.130
And what, in God's name,
is post mortem presentation?

12:20.261 --> 12:22.393
How the victims
look after death.

12:22.524 --> 12:24.569
An important metric.

12:24.700 --> 12:26.571
[DRY CHUCKLE]

12:26.702 --> 12:28.051
You can go now.

12:38.975 --> 12:40.629
I know, I know.

12:40.760 --> 12:42.849
You needn't
give me a lecture.
You're right.

12:42.979 --> 12:44.981
This won't do.

12:45.112 --> 12:47.592
Promise me to put an end
to this monstrosity.

12:47.723 --> 12:49.725
The boffins come up
with this clever stuff

12:49.856 --> 12:51.074
and it's hard
not to get drawn in.

12:51.205 --> 12:52.728
Promise me.

12:52.859 --> 12:54.904
There is a moral argument
to be made.

12:57.646 --> 12:58.908
Oh, really?

13:00.692 --> 13:03.347
In cold numbers of human death
and injury caused,

13:03.478 --> 13:06.698
gas is actually no worse than
aerial bombing and artillery.

13:06.829 --> 13:09.310
Except there's
no structural damage.
See, that's the thing.

13:09.440 --> 13:11.051
No, Jimmy.
That is not the thing.

13:14.663 --> 13:16.099
You're right.[KNOCKS ON TABLE]

13:16.230 --> 13:19.015
It won't do.
I'll put a stop to it.

13:19.146 --> 13:20.451
[STAMMERS]
I'll-- I will.

13:23.759 --> 13:25.630
ARCHBISHOP POTTER [ON TV]: <i>
No, it is not famine...[DOOR OPENS]</i>

13:25.761 --> 13:29.112
<i>or disease
that will bring humanity low.</i>

13:29.243 --> 13:32.724
<i>It is not Lord Harwood
and his fascist cronies.</i>

13:32.855 --> 13:35.510
<i>We'll see them off.What are you watching?</i>

13:35.640 --> 13:38.426
<i>The nuclear bomb, my friends.It was cowboys.</i>

13:38.556 --> 13:41.429
<i>That's the enemy.</i>

13:41.559 --> 13:44.519
<i>They say the bomb
brings peace.[SIGHS]</i>

13:44.649 --> 13:46.260
<i>Those are the dread--</i>

13:46.390 --> 13:48.349
[TURNS OFF TV]

13:48.479 --> 13:51.743
Cup of tea?I'm having a sherry.

13:51.874 --> 13:54.355
I'll put the kettle on.
I've got good news.

13:54.485 --> 13:55.399
[WARILY]
What's that then?

13:58.141 --> 14:00.491
-We've got the money.
-What money?

14:00.622 --> 14:02.450
We've got enough money now
for the bribes

14:02.580 --> 14:05.061
and the transit papers
and the visas.

14:05.192 --> 14:06.628
We're going
to America, Mom.

14:06.758 --> 14:08.499
A new life.

14:08.630 --> 14:11.763
Just now on the telly,
a man in America died

14:11.894 --> 14:14.114
from a bear
having a go at him.

14:14.244 --> 14:16.507
They get up to all sorts,
the animals over there.

14:16.638 --> 14:17.987
Not everywhere.

14:19.162 --> 14:20.250
Not in the cities.

14:21.730 --> 14:23.340
I keep telling you
I'm not going

14:23.471 --> 14:25.952
and you keep acting
as though you can't hear me.

14:26.082 --> 14:28.563
"A new life," he says.
What am I going to do
with a new life?

14:28.693 --> 14:31.174
Well, I'm not gonna
leave you here, am I?

14:31.305 --> 14:33.394
What if the neighbors
came round and saw you
like this?

14:34.786 --> 14:36.136
Like what?

14:36.266 --> 14:37.920
There's cobwebs
on the mantel

14:38.051 --> 14:40.923
and you're on the sherry
and chips watching <i>Bonanza.</i>

14:41.054 --> 14:44.579
If Dad was here he'd say,
"Where's your gumption, Mother?"

14:44.709 --> 14:46.320
He'd say,
"Pull your socks up."

14:46.450 --> 14:48.452
And I'd tell him where
to shove his bloody socks.

14:48.583 --> 14:50.367
And bugger
the neighbors!

14:52.761 --> 14:56.112
They point at me
and whisper.

14:56.243 --> 14:58.375
There's her
whose son killed his father.

14:58.506 --> 15:00.334
Stay away from her.
I can't even look at you

15:00.464 --> 15:01.901
without thinking
about what happened.

15:08.646 --> 15:10.605
[♪♪♪]

15:12.520 --> 15:14.087
That's all
in the past, Mom.

15:17.655 --> 15:20.397
We have to try
to move forward.

15:20.528 --> 15:23.096
I'm sorry.

15:23.226 --> 15:25.054
I shouldn't
have said that.

15:26.838 --> 15:28.275
Sorry.

15:28.405 --> 15:29.929
That's alright, Mom.

15:34.672 --> 15:36.674
I don't want
to move forward, Alfie.

15:38.850 --> 15:41.505
I just want
to end my life here,

15:41.636 --> 15:44.334
and sooner
rather than later.

15:44.465 --> 15:46.075
In a place I'm used to.

15:54.344 --> 15:56.390
Least said
soonest mended, eh?

15:56.520 --> 15:58.087
[DRY CHUCKLE]

16:03.310 --> 16:04.615
I'll put the kettle on.

16:11.927 --> 16:13.363
[OBJECTS CLATTER]

16:19.935 --> 16:22.111
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

16:31.860 --> 16:33.514
Pleasure
to see you, ma'am.

16:33.644 --> 16:34.558
What brings you
to London?

16:34.689 --> 16:36.343
The food.
Mmm.

16:36.473 --> 16:38.432
Don't get me started.

16:38.562 --> 16:41.565
I'm on route to Moscow.
Figure I'd stop by.

16:41.696 --> 16:43.611
There's a project underway
that's best discussed

16:43.741 --> 16:45.961
face to face.
Yes, ma'am.

16:46.092 --> 16:48.746
We have a problem
with the hydrogen bomb.

16:48.877 --> 16:52.707
Well, it's a great product,
but the public don't like it.

16:52.837 --> 16:54.752
Image wise,
the nuclear disarmament folks

16:54.883 --> 16:56.406
have done a darn good job

16:56.537 --> 16:58.582
of painting us
as greedy warmongers.

16:58.713 --> 17:00.541
We're over it.

17:00.671 --> 17:03.979
We're going to start kicking
some public relations butt.

17:04.110 --> 17:07.026
[DUBIOUS]
It sounds like an idea.

17:07.156 --> 17:10.377
The top anti-nuclear
campaigner in England

17:10.507 --> 17:12.248
is Archbishop Potter,

17:12.379 --> 17:14.946
Prime Minister of
The English League.

17:15.077 --> 17:17.427
Now, he's got
beaucoup moral authority,

17:17.558 --> 17:20.691
and he is highly
problematic to kill.

17:20.822 --> 17:22.867
So what do we do?

17:22.998 --> 17:25.522
Take away
his moral authority, I suppose.

17:27.350 --> 17:28.482
Can you say that
with a smile?

17:28.612 --> 17:30.440
Do I have to?

17:30.571 --> 17:32.660
Politics is dirty,
Thomas.

17:32.790 --> 17:35.271
You got to enjoy playing
in the dirt.

17:35.402 --> 17:37.708
I follow
policy directives.

17:37.839 --> 17:40.102
Whether or not
I enjoy the task.

17:42.887 --> 17:45.890
I'm glad
to hear you say so.

17:46.021 --> 17:48.632
I haven't gotten to the part
you really won't enjoy.

17:52.201 --> 17:54.377
[LIVELY JAZZ MUSIC
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

17:54.508 --> 17:55.683
Hello, Alfie.

17:55.813 --> 17:56.771
Evening.

17:56.901 --> 17:58.468
Join us.

17:58.599 --> 17:59.817
I wanted a word
with your girl here,

17:59.948 --> 18:01.428
but I can come back later
if you're busy.

18:01.558 --> 18:03.995
Nah, we're just talking
a bit of business.
Oh?

18:04.126 --> 18:05.997
I was just saying to Sand here,
I've been in discussions

18:06.128 --> 18:07.912
with the manager
of the Hippodrome.

18:08.043 --> 18:10.306
He's figured of offering her
a shot as an opening act.

18:10.437 --> 18:11.873
[SANDRA CHUCKLES]
Nice.

18:12.003 --> 18:13.788
We've got to choose
the right repertoire,

18:13.918 --> 18:16.617
you know, work on
her stagecraft as we call it,

18:16.747 --> 18:18.967
but things
are looking really good.

18:19.098 --> 18:20.751
SANDRA:
Dad says we have to strike
while the iron's hot

18:20.882 --> 18:23.711
and all that--
I don't think I'm ready.

18:23.841 --> 18:26.105
Oh, give over.
Look at you.

18:26.235 --> 18:28.498
You're beautiful,
you sing like a fucking bird,

18:28.629 --> 18:30.239
what more could you want,
am I right?

18:30.370 --> 18:31.501
He's right.

18:32.763 --> 18:34.113
Sky's the limit,
Sands.

18:36.550 --> 18:38.726
Right, I'll leave
you two lovebirds to it.

18:38.856 --> 18:41.642
Gotta piss. Me bladder's
like a prune these days.

18:41.772 --> 18:43.557
Don't do anything
I wouldn't do.

18:43.687 --> 18:45.254
SANDRA:
Dad!

18:48.039 --> 18:49.389
Go on then.

18:49.519 --> 18:50.433
What?

18:50.564 --> 18:52.435
You wanted a word.

18:52.566 --> 18:53.915
Right.
Yeah, I do.

18:54.045 --> 18:56.047
Don't worry,
I won't give you the elbow

18:56.178 --> 18:58.137
when I'm rich and famous,
if that's what you're
worried about.

18:58.267 --> 19:00.617
That's, that's good.
Yeah, no, it's some--

19:00.748 --> 19:02.445
You can be my bodyguard.

19:02.576 --> 19:04.360
We'll be flying around
in airplanes and that.

19:04.491 --> 19:05.753
It'll be
ever so glamorous.

19:05.883 --> 19:09.626
Sounds nice.Well, you know me, I'm loyal.

19:09.757 --> 19:12.499
Yeah, you are.

19:12.629 --> 19:13.761
[DRY CHUCKLE]

19:14.979 --> 19:16.546
Why you looking sad?

19:16.677 --> 19:19.288
I'm not,
I'm just thinking...

19:21.072 --> 19:22.944
What the fuck's
he doing here?

19:23.074 --> 19:25.816
SANDRA: Who?Thomas Wayne.

19:26.948 --> 19:27.992
I, um, I better go

19:28.123 --> 19:29.516
and say hello.

19:29.646 --> 19:30.691
We'll talk later, yeah?

19:39.395 --> 19:40.570
[JAZZ SONG ENDS]

19:40.701 --> 19:42.181
Mr. Wayne?

19:44.487 --> 19:46.576
Alfred!

19:46.707 --> 19:49.666
What a--
What a pleasant surprise.

19:52.408 --> 19:53.322
You work here?

19:53.453 --> 19:54.454
It's my club.

19:56.282 --> 20:00.590
[STAMMERS]
Wow, uh, that's excellent.

20:00.721 --> 20:02.549
You're doing
very well then. Bravo.

20:02.679 --> 20:03.985
You were home
in the States.

20:04.115 --> 20:06.335
Well, I was.

20:06.466 --> 20:07.423
I'm back.

20:07.554 --> 20:09.686
Welcome back then,
I suppose.

20:09.817 --> 20:11.819
Thomas, my dear,
how are you?

20:11.949 --> 20:14.648
Hello,
I'm Aleister Crowley.

20:14.778 --> 20:16.084
Alfred Pennyworth.

20:16.215 --> 20:18.913
Ah, the notorious
Alfred Pennyworth.

20:19.043 --> 20:21.089
I've heard
so much about you.

20:21.220 --> 20:23.134
What a lovely place
you have.

20:23.265 --> 20:25.049
I thought
you'd look more butch.

20:25.180 --> 20:28.575
You're so young
and pretty.

20:28.705 --> 20:30.751
Alright.

20:30.881 --> 20:32.448
Nice to meet you,
Mr. Crowley.

20:32.579 --> 20:35.016
Sheri...
- Yes, Alfie.

20:35.146 --> 20:36.800
Take good care
of these gentlemen for me.

20:36.931 --> 20:38.802
Mr. Wayne's an old friend.

20:38.933 --> 20:40.369
SHERI:
Will do, Alfie.

20:40.500 --> 20:41.675
Gentlemen...

20:41.805 --> 20:42.893
Come with me.

20:47.202 --> 20:48.595
SHERI:
Here we are.

20:48.725 --> 20:50.031
What can I get you?

20:50.161 --> 20:52.251
Gin and tonic,
please, my dear.

20:53.948 --> 20:54.992
A glass of milk.
- Sure.

20:59.040 --> 21:01.434
You might have chosen
a more discreet place
to meet.

21:01.564 --> 21:03.131
Oh, don't worry.

21:03.262 --> 21:05.568
Tout le monde gathers here.

21:05.699 --> 21:09.790
One might bump into anyone
without arousing suspicion.

21:09.920 --> 21:11.879
What can I do for you,
Thomas?

21:12.009 --> 21:14.490
I was surprised
to hear from you.

21:14.621 --> 21:17.014
We parted
in such acrimony.

21:17.145 --> 21:19.452
Yeah,
I was surprised myself.

21:22.324 --> 21:26.807
My superiors
have a proposal for you.

21:26.937 --> 21:29.853
You have superiors?
You astonish me.

21:29.984 --> 21:32.247
Tell all.

21:32.378 --> 21:33.857
We gather
you're very well connected

21:33.988 --> 21:35.119
inside the Raven Union.

21:35.250 --> 21:36.643
You gather correctly.

21:36.773 --> 21:38.645
But...

21:38.775 --> 21:42.562
you're held
at arms length,
in the shadows.

21:42.692 --> 21:44.738
Because you do
the squalid things

21:44.868 --> 21:47.610
that other people
find repugnant.

21:49.003 --> 21:51.919
A sort of carrion bird.

21:52.049 --> 21:53.834
Precisely.

21:53.964 --> 21:56.315
I'm loving
the proposal so far.

21:58.708 --> 22:02.364
A close friendship
with a U.S. agency

22:02.495 --> 22:04.801
would elevate your status
inside the Union, would it not?

22:04.932 --> 22:06.847
You intrigue me.
Go on.

22:09.676 --> 22:14.202
If a particular individual,

22:14.333 --> 22:17.336
identified as harmful
to Anglo-American relations,

22:17.466 --> 22:20.687
if that person suffered
some sort of...

22:20.817 --> 22:22.558
scandal,

22:22.689 --> 22:24.386
driving them
from public life...

22:26.170 --> 22:31.915
Langley would find a way
of showing gratitude.

22:33.134 --> 22:34.614
I accept your proposal.

22:36.006 --> 22:37.486
Who's my pigeon?

22:39.314 --> 22:40.663
Archbishop Potter.

22:47.801 --> 22:50.499
Archbishop Potter?

22:52.414 --> 22:55.374
Prime Minister
of the English League.

22:57.071 --> 22:58.899
Pillar of morality.

23:02.903 --> 23:05.384
Difficult,
but not impossible.

23:07.037 --> 23:09.213
Consider it done.

23:09.344 --> 23:12.391
I'm sorry that you're
so personally conflicted.

23:12.521 --> 23:15.785
My personal feelings
are neither here nor there.

23:15.916 --> 23:18.135
I have only one condition.

23:18.266 --> 23:19.702
Don't give me

23:19.833 --> 23:21.661
any of your soul selling
drivel.

23:21.791 --> 23:25.099
No, no, you've
already sold your soul.

23:27.362 --> 23:29.146
All I want...

23:29.277 --> 23:30.757
is a kiss.

23:30.887 --> 23:34.064
[INCREDULOUS LAUGH]

23:34.195 --> 23:35.805
God loves you, Thomas,

23:35.936 --> 23:40.244
but He's very judgmental,
isn't He?

23:40.375 --> 23:42.290
Satan doesn't judge.

23:42.421 --> 23:45.424
He adores every part of you.

23:45.554 --> 23:49.906
Even the squalid
lust for advancement
that led you here.

23:50.037 --> 23:52.561
All he wants in return,
is a little respect.

23:53.693 --> 23:56.086
A gesture of friendship.

23:58.132 --> 23:59.133
You're serious?

23:59.263 --> 24:01.135
Always.

24:08.316 --> 24:09.839
[WHISPERS]
Goddamn it...

24:35.865 --> 24:37.867
Thank you.

24:37.998 --> 24:40.261
AZIZ:
Manchester and Liverpool
can hold out for now at least.

24:40.391 --> 24:41.915
If we send them
more men and supplies,

24:42.045 --> 24:44.134
they may last
a couple of months more,

24:44.265 --> 24:46.180
but they will still be defeated
in the end.

24:46.310 --> 24:48.051
ARCHBISHOP POTTER:
I won't hear such talk.

24:48.182 --> 24:49.749
We must think positively.

24:49.879 --> 24:52.055
There is always hope.Hear hear!

24:52.186 --> 24:53.840
With all due respect,
Prime Minister,

24:53.970 --> 24:55.798
I am thinking positively.

24:55.929 --> 24:58.235
We must use the time
and the resources we still have

24:58.366 --> 25:00.194
to build better defenses
for London.

25:00.324 --> 25:03.589
I disagree. We cannot afford
to lose any more territory.

25:03.719 --> 25:07.070
We must resolve
to hold Manchester
and Liverpool at all costs.

25:07.201 --> 25:09.203
Resolution is all very well,
Mr. Ripper,

25:09.333 --> 25:11.205
but it's
no impedance to tanks.

25:11.335 --> 25:13.686
Are they really
truly doomed?

25:13.816 --> 25:15.557
They've done jolly well
so far.

25:15.688 --> 25:18.473
Doomed, ma'am, and draining
vital resources from London.

25:18.604 --> 25:20.388
RIPPER:
For a policeman,
you're very sure

25:20.519 --> 25:22.912
of your military expertise.

25:23.043 --> 25:24.479
Are gravediggers
any more qualified?

25:24.610 --> 25:26.960
Chair recognizes
the Woodcraft Folk.

25:30.224 --> 25:32.748
Speaking as a person
of proud Cornish descent,

25:32.879 --> 25:35.011
I'd like to point out,
the all too typical

25:35.142 --> 25:37.797
London-centric focus
of this debate.Oh, my God.

25:37.927 --> 25:41.322
Your point is
well taken, young man.

25:41.452 --> 25:44.543
Let us take a brief moment
to send our prayers and thoughts

25:44.673 --> 25:48.982
to the people of Cornwall
and the Channel Islands,

25:49.112 --> 25:51.375
fighting the good fight
alongside us.

25:51.506 --> 25:53.987
[♪♪♪]

25:58.861 --> 26:01.211
- Operator.
- Hello, Operator.

26:01.342 --> 26:04.475
Put us through to Raven Union HQ
switchboard in Watford, please.

26:04.606 --> 26:07.522
- Right away.
- Raven Union headquarters.

26:07.653 --> 26:10.220
Hello, Lord Harwood's
office, please.

26:10.351 --> 26:12.745
<i>SECRETARY [OVER PHONE]:
What's this regarding, please?</i>

26:12.875 --> 26:14.790
That's my business, pet.

26:14.921 --> 26:17.271
You can say it's a friend
of his Lordship.

26:17.401 --> 26:19.708
[SHEEP BAAING IN DISTANCE][PHONE RINGING WITHIN]

26:24.147 --> 26:25.061
Leader's office.

26:25.192 --> 26:27.237
Good morning.

26:27.368 --> 26:29.805
May I speak to his Lordship,
if you'd be so kind.

26:29.936 --> 26:31.459
Name and purpose of call?

26:31.590 --> 26:33.722
<i>It's a personal matter.
We're old friends.</i>

26:33.853 --> 26:34.854
Name?

26:36.029 --> 26:37.508
Tell him it's Bet.

26:37.639 --> 26:39.380
I'm in a spot of bother
and I need his help.

26:39.510 --> 26:41.077
Thank you, madame.
Your call has been logged

26:41.208 --> 26:42.862
and will receive
the appropriate attention.

26:42.992 --> 26:44.951
No, pet.
you don't understand.

26:45.081 --> 26:46.517
<i>I need to speak to him.</i>

26:46.648 --> 26:49.782
That's not how it works.
Good day to you.

26:49.912 --> 26:52.262
Hel--? Hello?

26:52.393 --> 26:53.742
Hello?

27:09.932 --> 27:11.455
Hello, Operator.

27:11.586 --> 27:14.067
Primrose 2154, please.

27:15.677 --> 27:17.636
Yes, I know
they're under siege.

27:17.766 --> 27:19.812
But they've still got phones,
haven't they?

27:19.942 --> 27:21.248
I need to speak
to my sister.

27:23.076 --> 27:24.904
Well, when are you
gonna switch 'em back on?

27:27.167 --> 27:28.821
That's
no bloody good, is it?

27:28.951 --> 27:30.779
Could take months.

27:30.910 --> 27:32.215
Thanks for nothing.

27:33.216 --> 27:35.784
[♪♪♪]

27:37.960 --> 27:39.135
KATIE:
Help!

27:40.223 --> 27:41.398
Help! I'm in here!

27:41.529 --> 27:45.054
Hellfire!
Why are you yelling?

27:45.185 --> 27:47.100
I told you
I'd come back, didn't I?

27:47.230 --> 27:48.841
You've been gone for hours.[BOTTLES CLINKING]

27:48.971 --> 27:51.539
Well, I'm back now.

27:51.670 --> 27:55.108
I've got bread
and then cheese

27:55.238 --> 27:57.197
margarine, and...

27:58.328 --> 27:59.808
a bottle of Tizer.

28:01.070 --> 28:02.550
I'll make
the sandwiches.

28:02.681 --> 28:04.857
You can help
if you like.

28:04.987 --> 28:05.945
We'll have a picnic.

28:06.075 --> 28:08.295
I thought
I was going to die.

28:08.425 --> 28:10.863
Death by being
on your own
for a bit?

28:10.993 --> 28:12.125
Terrible way to go.

28:12.255 --> 28:14.344
I was scared
you wouldn't come back.

28:14.475 --> 28:16.042
Don't be silly.

28:16.172 --> 28:19.741
Now then,
I'll uncuff you,

28:19.872 --> 28:22.091
but you'll have to promise
not to play silly buggers.

28:22.222 --> 28:24.006
-Alright?
-I promise.

28:33.363 --> 28:36.105
Honestly, how
a nervous nelly like you

28:36.236 --> 28:38.455
could go around
doing terrorism?

28:38.586 --> 28:40.370
You must have been
shitting yourself.

28:40.501 --> 28:42.938
I'm not a terrorist.

28:43.069 --> 28:44.984
So you keep saying.I'm not.

28:45.114 --> 28:49.336
I'd like to believe you, duck,
I would,

28:49.466 --> 28:51.555
but they do it
by science now,

28:51.686 --> 28:53.906
identifying subversives.

28:54.036 --> 28:54.950
They've got machines.

28:55.081 --> 28:56.952
American machines.

28:57.083 --> 28:59.389
The yanks aren't going
to get it wrong, are they?

28:59.520 --> 29:01.174
They're sending
a bastard to the moon.

29:01.304 --> 29:02.958
I told you,
I'm an art student.

29:03.089 --> 29:05.178
I go to Norwich Poly.

29:05.308 --> 29:07.006
That reminds me.

29:16.145 --> 29:18.017
You could do us
a drawing, eh?

29:19.235 --> 29:21.455
Take your mind off things.

29:21.585 --> 29:24.110
I don't feel like drawing.

29:24.240 --> 29:26.590
Go on.
You can draw me.

29:26.721 --> 29:28.027
I don't want to.

29:30.072 --> 29:31.291
Doesn't have to be me.

29:33.075 --> 29:34.773
Use your imagination.

29:35.686 --> 29:37.950
I don't want to draw.

29:39.342 --> 29:40.909
Oh, I see.

29:42.432 --> 29:44.565
You're not
an artist, are you?

29:44.695 --> 29:46.132
That was lies.

29:46.262 --> 29:48.090
You don't want to draw

29:48.221 --> 29:50.614
because you'll show yourself up
to be a bloody terrorist.

29:50.745 --> 29:52.051
That is not--

29:52.181 --> 29:53.661
You...

29:53.792 --> 29:56.925
Okay, I'll
draw something.

29:57.056 --> 29:58.622
Good lass.

29:58.753 --> 30:00.189
[TOOLS CLATTERING]

30:03.453 --> 30:05.238
I'll know
if you're any good, mind.

30:05.368 --> 30:08.458
My little sister
were mad for drawing.

30:08.589 --> 30:10.460
Years after she'd gone
we'd find her pencils

30:10.591 --> 30:12.245
down the settee.

30:12.375 --> 30:14.987
[♪♪♪]

30:22.255 --> 30:24.344
[SCRIBBLING]

30:29.610 --> 30:30.829
[KATIE GRUNTS]

30:33.570 --> 30:34.702
Why'd you do that?

30:34.833 --> 30:36.660
Please let me go!
Please!

30:36.791 --> 30:38.837
I've told you more than once
why that's not on.

30:38.967 --> 30:41.709
Why can't you see sense?Because you're crazy!

30:41.840 --> 30:44.103
I'm--
I'm trying to help you.

30:44.233 --> 30:45.495
I am.

30:45.626 --> 30:46.845
MILITIA MAN:
Oi!

30:48.455 --> 30:52.459
This area is closed
by order of county marshals.

30:52.589 --> 30:54.156
Sorry, duck.

30:54.287 --> 30:56.463
Didn't see the signs.
We'll be off.

30:56.593 --> 30:57.986
What were you doin'?

31:00.162 --> 31:01.120
Having a snog.

31:02.208 --> 31:03.644
BET:
Not illegal, is it?

31:03.774 --> 31:06.212
Let's see
your ID cards.

31:06.342 --> 31:08.997
-Left 'em at home.
-You're coming with us then.

31:10.085 --> 31:12.174
[MEN GRUNTING]

31:31.411 --> 31:32.586
[YELLS, THEN GRUNTS IN PAIN]

31:35.154 --> 31:36.546
Thank you.

31:36.677 --> 31:38.287
You took long enough.

31:39.854 --> 31:41.638
[BET GRUNTS, SIGHS]

31:41.769 --> 31:44.380
Are they--
Are they alright?

31:44.511 --> 31:46.121
Yeah. Not to worry.

31:46.252 --> 31:47.209
[BOTTLE SHATTERS]

31:52.562 --> 31:54.347
[MAN GRUNTS][KATIE GASPING]

31:59.352 --> 32:01.049
No!
[MAN GAGGING]

32:02.442 --> 32:03.660
[GLASS SHATTERS]What?

32:03.791 --> 32:05.662
Why did you do that?

32:05.793 --> 32:08.143
Can't have 'em telling
where we are.

32:08.274 --> 32:10.232
We'll have hundreds
of the buggers after us.

32:12.626 --> 32:14.410
[KATIE GAGS AND RETCHES]

32:16.282 --> 32:18.110
You're a bit soft
for a terrorist, innit ya?

32:18.240 --> 32:19.807
I'm not a terrorist!

32:19.938 --> 32:22.418
Oh, keep your knickers on.

32:22.549 --> 32:24.072
I'm just teasing you.

32:31.645 --> 32:32.951
Best be off, eh?

32:34.517 --> 32:37.216
[♪♪♪]

32:40.262 --> 32:42.221
[PHONE RINGS]

32:42.351 --> 32:43.918
Hello?

32:44.049 --> 32:45.615
WOMAN [OVER PHONE]: <i>
Hello, is Alfie there, please?</i>

32:45.746 --> 32:47.574
I'm afraid he's at work.

32:47.704 --> 32:50.316
<i>You're sure he's not there?</i>

32:50.446 --> 32:51.752
I just said that, didn't I?

32:51.882 --> 32:53.710
<i>Just want to be
on the safe side.</i>

33:02.502 --> 33:04.330
[MRS. PENNYWORTH SCREAMING]

33:04.460 --> 33:05.592
Get your hands off me!

33:05.722 --> 33:07.333
Get your filthy hands off me!

33:07.463 --> 33:08.464
Who the fuck are you?!

33:08.595 --> 33:10.597
Get off! Get off!

33:10.727 --> 33:11.685
Get off!

33:11.815 --> 33:12.816
[MRS. PENNYWORTH EXCLAIMS]

33:12.947 --> 33:14.340
Fucking asshole!

33:14.470 --> 33:16.124
You fucking bastards!

33:17.821 --> 33:20.259
Thank you.SANDRA: Alfie!

33:21.782 --> 33:24.263
Guess what?
What?

33:25.612 --> 33:27.309
I'm on at the Hippodrome!

33:27.440 --> 33:29.268
They said yes!Hey! That's brilliant!

33:29.398 --> 33:31.835
Well done, girl![SANDRA GIGGLES]

33:31.966 --> 33:33.794
I'm bottom of the bill
and I only sing one song,

33:33.924 --> 33:35.448
but still, the Hippodrome.

33:35.578 --> 33:37.841
Hey, I'm really,
really proud of you.

33:37.972 --> 33:39.626
It's three weeks
from Saturday.

33:39.756 --> 33:41.280
You'll come, won't you?

33:41.410 --> 33:42.368
Make sure
you haven't got a job on.

33:42.498 --> 33:44.239
Um, yeah.
'Course.

33:44.370 --> 33:46.502
I'll try.You'll try?

33:46.633 --> 33:47.764
Yeah.

33:47.895 --> 33:50.289
No.
No, I'll be there.

33:50.419 --> 33:52.247
But you never know,
do you?

33:52.378 --> 33:53.335
There's a war on.

33:53.466 --> 33:54.641
Don't say that.

33:54.771 --> 33:56.817
What song
you going to sing?

33:56.947 --> 33:59.298
Well, Dad wants me
to sing a ballad,

33:59.428 --> 34:00.777
but I'll be ever so nervous

34:00.908 --> 34:02.562
and my ballads are wobbly
when I'm nervous...

34:02.692 --> 34:04.651
I think I'd rather do more of
a sing along sort of number.

34:04.781 --> 34:06.870
What do you reckon?

34:07.001 --> 34:09.047
Um, I'll have a think.

34:09.177 --> 34:11.875
It'd be nice if I sing
a song you choose.

34:12.006 --> 34:13.747
It was you that gave me
the courage to do this.

34:13.877 --> 34:17.620
No, no, it's you
that's done this.

34:17.751 --> 34:21.363
You, with your talent
and your goodness.

34:21.494 --> 34:23.496
Nothing to do with me.
You remember that.

34:25.846 --> 34:28.196
MAN: Sandra...Yeah?

34:30.981 --> 34:33.245
You had something
to wanted to tell me?

34:34.811 --> 34:36.552
No. No, never mind.

34:36.683 --> 34:38.206
Not important.

34:38.337 --> 34:39.381
Okay.

34:50.218 --> 34:53.656
Texas hold 'em is
all they play in Las Vegas.

34:53.787 --> 34:57.921
I'll get the hang of it,
but it's a strange game.

34:58.052 --> 35:00.794
It's more of a knife fight
than a chess match.

35:02.491 --> 35:04.102
[SIGHS]

35:05.712 --> 35:07.235
Problem?

35:07.366 --> 35:08.758
Nah. Cushty.

35:10.586 --> 35:12.284
You don't have to go.

35:12.414 --> 35:13.720
Do what?

35:13.850 --> 35:15.287
I'm going,
but you don't have to.

35:15.417 --> 35:16.636
What are you on about?

35:18.072 --> 35:20.640
You're mad.
I'm going.

35:23.599 --> 35:24.557
How old's that sandwich?

35:24.687 --> 35:26.298
Old.

35:29.779 --> 35:32.565
[PHONE RINGING]

35:32.695 --> 35:34.393
If it's the Queen,
I'm not here.

35:35.437 --> 35:36.482
Hello?

35:36.612 --> 35:39.441
Bazza, is Alfie there?

35:39.572 --> 35:40.747
He's right here.

35:40.877 --> 35:42.662
Alfie,
it's your mother.

35:44.707 --> 35:45.665
Mom?

35:45.795 --> 35:48.450
Alfie...

35:48.581 --> 35:49.712
I've been kidnapped.

35:49.843 --> 35:51.801
Are you alright?
Have they hurt you?

35:53.934 --> 35:55.805
I'm alright.

35:55.936 --> 35:57.067
They want me to read
this letter to you.

35:57.198 --> 35:58.765
It's going
to be alright, Mom.

35:58.895 --> 36:01.811
<i>"If you want
to see me alive again,</i>

36:01.942 --> 36:06.773
"come alone with $20,000

36:06.903 --> 36:09.471
"to the corner of
Battlebridge Road

36:09.602 --> 36:11.821
<i>"and York Way.</i>

36:11.952 --> 36:15.825
<i>"They know you've got the money
so don't try to bargain.</i>

36:15.956 --> 36:17.827
"You've got one hour.

36:17.958 --> 36:21.091
Alone, or I'm dead."

36:21.222 --> 36:23.006
It's going
to be alright, Mom.

36:23.137 --> 36:24.399
Don't do it, Alfie!

36:24.530 --> 36:25.618
[GASPS][HANGS UP PHONE]

36:25.748 --> 36:27.359
[DIAL TONE]

36:27.489 --> 36:28.795
Mom's been taken.

36:28.925 --> 36:30.579
They want the money
in Kings Cross.

36:30.710 --> 36:32.581
One hour.I'll get the car...

36:32.712 --> 36:35.584
[BOTH GRUNT]You silly cow!
What d'you do that for?

36:38.674 --> 36:41.286
Daveboy!
Boots on!

36:41.416 --> 36:43.331
[♪♪♪]

36:59.565 --> 37:01.349
It costs nothing
to be polite.

37:02.698 --> 37:04.265
Do you want
to fucking die?

37:07.094 --> 37:08.530
I'm not bothered.

37:09.923 --> 37:11.403
Couldn't care less.

37:18.061 --> 37:20.281
You'd offer me a glass of
water if you was a gentleman.

37:25.068 --> 37:27.680
[WATER POURS FROM FAUCET, STOPS]

37:31.510 --> 37:32.772
Very kind.

37:40.997 --> 37:43.130
Who are you people?

37:43.261 --> 37:44.827
That's why we have masks.

37:44.958 --> 37:46.394
So you don't know who we are.

37:47.569 --> 37:48.831
Must be very hot.

38:05.761 --> 38:06.980
MALE DRIVER:
Give me the bag.

38:07.110 --> 38:08.547
Where's me mom?

38:08.677 --> 38:10.157
Give me the bag
and we'll let her go.

38:10.288 --> 38:12.855
Fuck off.
No mom, no bag.

38:12.986 --> 38:14.683
That ain't the plan.

38:14.814 --> 38:18.034
It's all there.
No trouble.

38:18.165 --> 38:20.733
But you got
to show me my mom first.
That's only reasonable.

38:20.863 --> 38:22.648
Give me the fucking bag, mate,
or we'll kill her!

38:22.778 --> 38:24.650
Not your shout, is it?

38:24.780 --> 38:26.869
You're an oily rag.

38:27.000 --> 38:30.699
Go and tell your guvnor that
I won't cough up
until I see my mom.

38:37.750 --> 38:38.968
Wait here.

38:46.889 --> 38:47.847
[PIERCING WHISTLE]

38:51.633 --> 38:52.547
I'm losing my touch.

38:52.678 --> 38:54.549
I told you two to stay away.

38:54.680 --> 38:55.768
Now get the fuck
out of here.

38:55.898 --> 38:56.812
Nah, it's only me.

38:56.943 --> 38:58.031
Bazza!

39:01.991 --> 39:03.515
Sorry.Now fucking leg it,

39:03.645 --> 39:04.777
before he comes back.

39:04.907 --> 39:06.866
Are you sure?Yes, get in the car.

39:06.996 --> 39:08.346
[SMALL DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE]

39:13.786 --> 39:14.917
[THUMP IN DISTANCE]

39:16.179 --> 39:18.878
[METALLIC CLATTERING
IN DISTANCE]

39:37.113 --> 39:38.767
Take out your gun
and drop it.

39:43.163 --> 39:44.512
[GUN CLATTERS]Get in.

39:59.701 --> 40:01.355
Only two of you?

40:01.486 --> 40:03.009
I know judo
and all that you know.

40:03.139 --> 40:04.184
From the army.

40:04.314 --> 40:06.099
[LAUGHING]
Try something.

40:06.229 --> 40:08.884
What's that?
A flare gun?

40:09.015 --> 40:10.625
I'm not a ship at sea.

40:10.756 --> 40:12.279
It's a .44 Magnum,

40:12.410 --> 40:13.585
and it'll take
your head off

40:13.715 --> 40:14.934
like a walnut whip.

40:15.064 --> 40:16.892
Nah. That's
a flare gun, mate.

40:17.023 --> 40:20.113
Are you sailors?
I know you're fucking amateurs.

40:20.243 --> 40:22.376
You're sailors, aren't you?
Jolly jack tars.

40:22.507 --> 40:25.858
Is that a flare gun? Is it?Oh no, I stand corrected.

40:25.988 --> 40:28.121
It's not a flare gun.[GRUNTS IN PAIN]

40:28.251 --> 40:30.123
You, keep drivin'.

40:30.253 --> 40:32.168
If you've hurt my mom...

40:32.299 --> 40:33.909
I don't even know
what I'll do.

40:34.040 --> 40:36.782
[GRUNTING IN PAIN]Steady on, mate!
She's alright!

40:36.912 --> 40:38.174
Look, it's only business,
and we're all businessmen.

40:38.305 --> 40:39.785
Businessmen?

40:39.915 --> 40:41.003
Take off your mask.

40:43.571 --> 40:45.660
I don't know you.
Who the fuck are you?

40:45.791 --> 40:46.966
We're just
hired hands, mate.

40:47.096 --> 40:48.271
Who's your guvnor?I don't know.

40:48.402 --> 40:50.665
Give over.I swear!

40:50.796 --> 40:52.145
He only hired us last week.

40:52.275 --> 40:53.973
We met him twice and he wears
a mask all the time.

40:54.103 --> 40:55.888
Like a secret mastermind
sort of thing.

40:56.018 --> 40:58.107
Calls himself Mr. X.Where were you taking me?

40:58.238 --> 41:00.501
DRIVER:
Caravan on Clerkenwell Fields.

41:00.632 --> 41:03.112
Who's there?
Your mum--
Well, a nice little old lady,

41:03.243 --> 41:04.984
I assume that's your mum--
and the guvnor.

41:05.114 --> 41:06.855
And three other blokes. Muscle.
I don't know who they are.

41:06.986 --> 41:08.988
What, they wear
masks too, do they?

41:09.118 --> 41:10.990
Ugh--
Please don't hit me again.

41:13.166 --> 41:14.907
Take the second left.

41:25.918 --> 41:26.962
Amateurs.

41:27.093 --> 41:28.616
[CHUCKLES]

41:55.295 --> 41:57.166
The money's all here.

41:58.820 --> 41:59.995
Where's me mom?

42:11.354 --> 42:12.965
Well, where's me mom?

42:15.010 --> 42:16.229
ALFIE:
Bring her out here.

42:19.145 --> 42:20.538
Your money's all there, mate.

42:22.714 --> 42:26.544
Hand her over
and I'll give this
to you, I walk away.

42:28.023 --> 42:30.243
But mom comes first.

42:30.373 --> 42:32.419
MRS. PENNYWORTH:
Alfie?!
Mom?

42:32.550 --> 42:33.812
MRS. PENNYWORTH:
Is that you?

42:33.942 --> 42:35.857
You alright?I'm alright, son.

42:35.988 --> 42:37.380
Don't give
the bastards a penny!

42:37.511 --> 42:40.035
MR. X: Shut it!Or else what?

42:40.166 --> 42:42.081
You leave this to me!

42:42.211 --> 42:43.343
MRS. PENNYWORTH:
You've worked hard
for that money!

42:43.473 --> 42:45.650
Mom! Be quiet
and let me handle this.

42:45.780 --> 42:49.871
MRS. PENNYWORTH:
Don't you tell me
to be quiet! You go away!

42:50.002 --> 42:52.178
That money's
for my grandchildren,

42:52.308 --> 42:55.398
if you ever settle down,
which you should.

42:55.529 --> 42:57.009
Not now, Mom!

42:57.139 --> 42:58.750
MRS. PENNYWORTH:
You promised me you that,

42:58.880 --> 42:59.968
and I'll die happy.

43:02.188 --> 43:03.581
For fuck's sake.

43:05.104 --> 43:06.932
Freeze!

43:07.062 --> 43:08.803
Toss your guns away.

43:08.934 --> 43:10.805
Now get on your knees,
hands on your head.

43:10.936 --> 43:12.328
Now!

43:12.459 --> 43:14.026
[TIRES SCREECHING]

43:20.336 --> 43:22.251
[GUNFIRE][PEOPLE CLAMORING]

43:22.382 --> 43:23.688
It's okay, I've got you.

43:23.818 --> 43:25.037
Yeah?
Yeah.

43:25.167 --> 43:26.125
[GUNFIRE;
MRS. PENNYWORTH SCREAMS]

43:32.871 --> 43:33.959
Stop!

43:34.089 --> 43:36.222
Hold your fire, boys!

43:39.094 --> 43:40.269
You alright?I'm alright.

43:40.400 --> 43:42.010
Are you alright?Yeah, I'm alright.

43:43.185 --> 43:44.317
Alfie!

43:47.276 --> 43:48.582
Get the-- Fuck.

43:48.713 --> 43:50.628
Be a good chap
and come quietly, would you?

43:59.593 --> 44:00.768
Alright, Daveboy?

44:02.204 --> 44:03.815
Oi, smashing.

44:03.945 --> 44:05.860
[POLICE RADIO CHATTER]

44:05.991 --> 44:07.514
Fuck.
They've got my money.

44:07.645 --> 44:09.385
You let them get away!What money is that?

44:09.516 --> 44:11.474
Ransom money.
They abducted my mom!

44:11.605 --> 44:14.477
What the fuck
are you doing here?

44:14.608 --> 44:16.349
Perhaps we got
the wrong end of the stick.

44:16.479 --> 44:18.438
We've been watching you
and we rather suspected

44:18.568 --> 44:20.353
you were meeting with the men
who took Colonel Salt.

44:20.483 --> 44:22.268
Oh...A division of spoils.

44:22.398 --> 44:24.009
This was not them?

44:24.139 --> 44:25.314
Why would you suspect that?

44:25.445 --> 44:26.838
Why do you suppose
I would suspect that?

44:26.968 --> 44:28.535
You're wrong.

44:28.666 --> 44:30.102
And that's
besides the point.

44:30.232 --> 44:33.018
You've buggered me
good and proper now.

44:33.148 --> 44:34.889
Mr. Aziz.

44:35.020 --> 44:36.369
I might have known.

44:36.499 --> 44:38.197
DAVEBOY:
You bastards.

44:38.327 --> 44:41.417
I was off
to fuck Doris Day.

44:42.592 --> 44:43.811
You're an albatross,
you are.

44:44.943 --> 44:46.292
Hmm.

44:46.422 --> 44:48.729
[♪♪♪]

44:53.603 --> 44:55.997
[CROW CAWS]

44:57.956 --> 44:59.697
[PANTING]

45:06.268 --> 45:07.400
Oh, God...

45:08.967 --> 45:10.272
Forgive me.

45:16.583 --> 45:17.497
[LOUD GRUNTING WITH EACH STRIKE]

45:17.627 --> 45:18.846
[GASPS]

45:20.065 --> 45:24.417
NUN:
Oh, sir! Don't do that.

45:24.547 --> 45:26.985
[CROWLEY SOBBING]

45:27.115 --> 45:28.160
Oh...

45:32.033 --> 45:33.861
Oh God, I beg you!

45:33.992 --> 45:35.384
Forgive me!

45:36.646 --> 45:37.865
Forgive me.

45:43.218 --> 45:47.440
My child, please stop.

45:49.398 --> 45:51.052
Tell me
what's wrong.

45:56.492 --> 45:58.320
Only God can help me.

46:02.107 --> 46:05.197
I talk with God
all the time.

46:06.720 --> 46:10.028
Perhaps I can help you
get in touch with him.

46:15.773 --> 46:18.471
Let's have
a cup of tea, shall we?

46:23.998 --> 46:27.480
ARCHBISHOP POTTER:
Would you like some liniment
for your head?

46:27.610 --> 46:29.308
You'll have a nasty bruise.

46:31.092 --> 46:34.400
A sign of piety
among the Saracen.

46:37.359 --> 46:40.058
Will you tell me
your troubles, young man?

46:41.842 --> 46:44.236
You don't have
to tell me anything of course.

46:45.715 --> 46:47.282
You don't have
to speak at all

46:47.413 --> 46:48.936
if you don't want to.

46:50.633 --> 46:54.812
Tea and biscuits is
often enough, don't you find?

46:56.422 --> 46:58.554
You know my troubles.

46:58.685 --> 47:01.383
How can
I know your troubles?

47:01.514 --> 47:03.124
Don't you know who I am?

47:04.647 --> 47:06.345
I know who you are.

47:06.475 --> 47:08.260
What do you know?

47:08.390 --> 47:12.655
You believe you're
a servant of the Devil.

47:12.786 --> 47:15.397
I've never suffered
such a delusion myself,

47:15.528 --> 47:18.487
so I can't truly know
your troubles.

47:18.618 --> 47:20.185
I can guess,

47:20.315 --> 47:22.361
but I don't want
to do that.

47:22.491 --> 47:24.842
I want to escape from him,

47:24.972 --> 47:26.408
but I don't know
if I have the strength.

47:26.539 --> 47:30.238
You have the strength.

47:30.369 --> 47:32.893
The Devil has
no servants.

47:33.024 --> 47:38.246
He's a ghost we conjure up
to explain away our sins.

47:39.682 --> 47:41.989
He's the dog
that ate your homework.

47:44.078 --> 47:47.603
ARCHBISHOP POTTER:
Let your mind dwell
in the light of God

47:47.734 --> 47:50.998
and he will disappear
like a shadow.

47:51.825 --> 47:53.044
I've seen him.

47:53.174 --> 47:55.263
I've touched him.

47:55.394 --> 47:57.352
He did evil things to me.

47:57.483 --> 47:59.528
I know he's real.

47:59.659 --> 48:01.400
More real than you or I.

48:02.836 --> 48:04.359
What did he do to you?

48:07.232 --> 48:09.147
It's not that
I don't want to tell you,

48:09.277 --> 48:11.758
but you wouldn't believe
or understand me.

48:11.889 --> 48:15.283
[SCOFFS]
You can let me try.

48:17.372 --> 48:20.158
I'm not sure you want
to go where I'll take you.

48:21.637 --> 48:24.031
Don't you worry about me.

48:30.385 --> 48:32.257
Close your eyes.

48:32.387 --> 48:34.172
[♪♪♪]

48:41.744 --> 48:44.530
Leave this world.

48:44.660 --> 48:49.535
Go down to the darkest depths
of your imagination.

48:49.665 --> 48:51.493
Then descend further.

48:53.669 --> 48:55.236
And further.

48:57.238 --> 48:59.588
Imagine feeling,

48:59.719 --> 49:05.290
in that moment of vile
unspeakable degradation,

49:05.420 --> 49:09.947
the most intense bliss.

49:10.077 --> 49:13.211
As if the universe trembled
at your touch

49:13.341 --> 49:16.475
and opened up like a flower.

49:27.703 --> 49:29.009
[EXHALES]

49:30.924 --> 49:34.406
I'm afraid my imagination
has no such depths.

49:34.536 --> 49:36.103
I could show you.

49:38.801 --> 49:41.500
But I wouldn't want
to do that.

49:41.630 --> 49:43.806
You seem like
a good kind man.

49:43.937 --> 49:45.417
[TEA CUP CLATTERING]

49:45.547 --> 49:47.332
I'm sorry to burden you
with my torments.

49:47.462 --> 49:49.421
Oh, heavens,
don't apologize.

49:49.551 --> 49:51.118
I'm here to help.

49:55.731 --> 49:59.474
What d'you mean exactly,

49:59.605 --> 50:02.173
you could show me?

50:02.303 --> 50:03.565
Those depths?

50:09.789 --> 50:11.660
[♪♪♪]
